The paper deals with a problem in signal processing and machine learning, specifically finding the sparsest vector in a subspace. This problem has connections to sparse dictionary learning, sparse PCA, and other related problems. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also proposes a nonconvex approach based on alternating directions, which is a common technique in machine learning and optimization, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) another likely sub-category. The paper also involves analyzing the performance of algorithms, which falls under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.NA (Numerical Analysis). Finally, the paper presents empirical results on sparse dictionary learning, which falls under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
